Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

Q Text:
Consider the following segments of java code.  Assume that there are no intentional syntax errors.

import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
public class Observer implements ActionListener {
  public void buildGUI () {
    JFrame frame = new JFrame();              
    JButton button = new JButton("Click me");
    frame.add(button);                   
    /* MISSING STATEMENT */                
    frame.setVisible(true);                   
  } // end method buildGUI

  public void actionPerformed (ActionEvent event) {
    System.out.println("Click");
  } // end method actionPerformed
} // end class Observer

Which of the following statements best replaces /* MISSING STATEMENT */ in the code segment above?

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Q Text:
Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
public class Observer implements ActionListener {
  public void buildGUI () {
    JFrame frame = new JFrame();              
    JButton button = new JButton("Click me");
    frame.add(button);                   
    /* MISSING STATEMENT */                
    frame.setVisible(true);                   
  } // end method buildGUI

  public void actionPerformed (ActionEvent event) {
    System.out.println("Click");
  } // end method actionPerformed
} // end class Observer

/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Q Title: CAC abcjk:EAC :SDF/Algorithms and Design:Concept and properties
Q Text:
Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

Q Title: CAC abc:EAC :PL/Event-Driven and Reactive Programming:Events and event handlers
Q Text:
Consider the following segments of java code.  Assume that there are no intentional syntax errors.

import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
public class Observer implements ActionListener {
  public void buildGUI () {
    JFrame frame = new JFrame();              
    JButton button = new JButton("Click me");
    frame.add(button);                   
    /* MISSING STATEMENT */                
    frame.setVisible(true);                   
  } // end method buildGUI

  public void actionPerformed (ActionEvent event) {
    System.out.println("Click");
  } // end method actionPerformed
} // end class Observer

Which of the following statements best replaces /* MISSING STATEMENT */ in the code segment above?

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];

  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

import javax.swing.*;

} // end class Observer

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Q Title: CAC abcjk:EAC :SDF/Algorithms and Design:Concept and properties
Q Text:
Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

Q Text:
Consider the following segments of java code.  Assume that there are no intentional syntax errors.

import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
public class Observer implements ActionListener {
  public void buildGUI () {
    JFrame frame = new JFrame();              
    JButton button = new JButton("Click me");
    frame.add(button);                   
    /* MISSING STATEMENT */                
    frame.setVisible(true);                   
  } // end method buildGUI

  public void actionPerformed (ActionEvent event) {
    System.out.println("Click");
  } // end method actionPerformed
} // end class Observer

Which of the following statements best replaces /* MISSING STATEMENT */ in the code segment above?

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Q Text:
Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Q Text:
Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Q Text:
Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Q Text:
Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

    /* MISSING STATEMENT */

  } // end method buildGUI

  public void actionPerformed (ActionEvent event) {
    System.out.println("Click");
  } // end method actionPerformed
} // end class Observer

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

Q Text:
Consider the following segments of java code.  Assume that there are no intentional syntax errors.

import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
public class Observer implements ActionListener {
  public void buildGUI () {
    JFrame frame = new JFrame();              
    JButton button = new JButton("Click me");
    frame.add(button);                   
    /* MISSING STATEMENT */                
    frame.setVisible(true);                   
  } // end method buildGUI

  public void actionPerformed (ActionEvent event) {
    System.out.println("Click");
  } // end method actionPerformed
} // end class Observer

Which of the following statements best replaces /* MISSING STATEMENT */ in the code segment above?

Consider the following code segment:

if (x % 2 == 0)
   x = x - 1;
if (x % 2 != 0)
  x = x + 1;

/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;

  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Q Title: CAC abcjk:EAC :SDF/Algorithms and Design:Concept and properties
Q Text:
Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

Q Title: CAC abc:EAC :PL/Event-Driven and Reactive Programming:Events and event handlers
Q Text:
Consider the following segments of java code.  Assume that there are no intentional syntax errors.

import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
public class Observer implements ActionListener {
  public void buildGUI () {
    JFrame frame = new JFrame();              
    JButton button = new JButton("Click me");
    frame.add(button);                   
    /* MISSING STATEMENT */                
    frame.setVisible(true);                   
  } // end method buildGUI

  public void actionPerformed (ActionEvent event) {
    System.out.println("Click");
  } // end method actionPerformed
} // end class Observer

Which of the following statements best replaces /* MISSING STATEMENT */ in the code segment above?

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Q Text:
Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Q Title: CAC abcjk:EAC :SDF/Algorithms and Design:Concept and properties
Q Text:
Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {

      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
public class Observer implements ActionListener {
  public void buildGUI () {
    JFrame frame = new JFrame();

    frame.add(button);                   
    /* MISSING STATEMENT */                
    frame.setVisible(true);                   
  } // end method buildGUI

  public void actionPerformed (ActionEvent event) {
    System.out.println("Click");
  } // end method actionPerformed
} // end class Observer

/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

import javax.swing.*;

  } // end method buildGUI

  public void actionPerformed (ActionEvent event) {

  } // end method actionPerformed
} // end class Observer

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Q Text:
Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Q Text:
Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Q Text:
Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

  } // end method actionPerformed

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

Q Text:
Consider the following segments of java code.  Assume that there are no intentional syntax errors.

import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
public class Observer implements ActionListener {
  public void buildGUI () {
    JFrame frame = new JFrame();              
    JButton button = new JButton("Click me");
    frame.add(button);                   
    /* MISSING STATEMENT */                
    frame.setVisible(true);                   
  } // end method buildGUI

  public void actionPerformed (ActionEvent event) {
    System.out.println("Click");
  } // end method actionPerformed
} // end class Observer

Which of the following statements best replaces /* MISSING STATEMENT */ in the code segment above?

Consider the following code segment:

if (x % 2 == 0)
   x = x - 1;
if (x % 2 != 0)
  x = x + 1;

/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;

  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Q Title: CAC abcjk:EAC :SDF/Algorithms and Design:Concept and properties
Q Text:
Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

Q Title: CAC abc:EAC :PL/Event-Driven and Reactive Programming:Events and event handlers
Q Text:
Consider the following segments of java code.  Assume that there are no intentional syntax errors.

import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
public class Observer implements ActionListener {
  public void buildGUI () {
    JFrame frame = new JFrame();              
    JButton button = new JButton("Click me");
    frame.add(button);                   
    /* MISSING STATEMENT */                
    frame.setVisible(true);                   
  } // end method buildGUI

  public void actionPerformed (ActionEvent event) {
    System.out.println("Click");
  } // end method actionPerformed
} // end class Observer

Which of the following statements best replaces /* MISSING STATEMENT */ in the code segment above?

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Q Text:
Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Q Text:
Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Q Title: CAC abcjk:EAC :SDF/Algorithms and Design:Concept and properties
Q Text:
Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

Q Text:
Consider the following segments of java code.  Assume that there are no intentional syntax errors.

import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
public class Observer implements ActionListener {
  public void buildGUI () {
    JFrame frame = new JFrame();              
    JButton button = new JButton("Click me");
    frame.add(button);                   
    /* MISSING STATEMENT */                
    frame.setVisible(true);                   
  } // end method buildGUI

  public void actionPerformed (ActionEvent event) {
    System.out.println("Click");
  } // end method actionPerformed
} // end class Observer

Which of the following statements best replaces /* MISSING STATEMENT */ in the code segment above?

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
public class Observer implements ActionListener {

    frame.add(button);                   
    /* MISSING STATEMENT */                
    frame.setVisible(true);                   
  } // end method buildGUI

  public void actionPerformed (ActionEvent event) {
    System.out.println("Click");
  } // end method actionPerformed
} // end class Observer

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Q Text:
Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the number of even values in array m.

Q Text:
Consider the following segments of java code.  Assume that there are no intentional syntax errors.

import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
public class Observer implements ActionListener {
  public void buildGUI () {
    JFrame frame = new JFrame();              
    JButton button = new JButton("Click me");
    frame.add(button);                   
    /* MISSING STATEMENT */                
    frame.setVisible(true);                   
  } // end method buildGUI

  public void actionPerformed (ActionEvent event) {
    System.out.println("Click");
  } // end method actionPerformed
} // end class Observer

Which of the following statements best replaces /* MISSING STATEMENT */ in the code segment above?

I.  The final value of x is always even.

II.  The final value of x is equal to its initial value when x is initially even.

III. The final value of x is equal to its initial value when x is initially odd.

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Q Title: CAC abcjk:EAC :SDF/Algorithms and Design:Concept and properties
Q Text:
Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).

public boolean isDecreasing() {

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

  } // end method actionPerformed

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

Q Text:
Consider the following segments of java code.  Assume that there are no intentional syntax errors.

import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
public class Observer implements ActionListener {
  public void buildGUI () {
    JFrame frame = new JFrame();              
    JButton button = new JButton("Click me");
    frame.add(button);                   
    /* MISSING STATEMENT */                
    frame.setVisible(true);                   
  } // end method buildGUI

  public void actionPerformed (ActionEvent event) {
    System.out.println("Click");
  } // end method actionPerformed
} // end class Observer

Which of the following statements best replaces /* MISSING STATEMENT */ in the code segment above?

*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for

} // end method isDecreasing

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.

private List<Integer> values;
/** @return true   if for every k in the range 0 < k < values.size(),
*                         values.get(k) is less than values.get(k-1).
*               false   otherwise
*/
public boolean isDecreasing() {
  boolean isDecr;
  /* statement 1 */
  for (int k = 1; k < values.size(); k++) {
    int prev = values.get(k-1).intValue();
    int curr = values.get(k).intValue();
    /* statement 2 */
  } // end for
  return isDecr;
} // end method isDecreasing
 
Consider the following replacements for statements 1 and 2
 
    /* statement 1 */             /* statement 2 */
 
I.   isDecr = true;                if (curr >= prev) isDecr = false;
 
II.  isDecr = false;               if (curr < prev) isDecr = true;
 
III. isDecr = true;                isDecr = isDecr && (curr < prev);
 
 
Which of the proposed replacements can be used so that isDecreasing() will work as intented?

Q Title: CAC abcjk:EAC :SDF/Algorithms and Design:Concept and properties
Q Text:
Consider the following instance variables and incomplete method that will be used for computing a final quiz score. A final quiz score is computed by adding all the quiz scores and dropping the lowest score from the total.  The method calculateFinalQuizScore performs the computation and updates the variable finalQuizScore.  Assume that the instance variables are properly initialized.

private int[] quizScores;
private int finalQuizScore;
public void calculateFinalQuizScore() {
  int total = 0;
  int least = quizScores[0];
  for (int k = 0; k < quizScores.length; k++) {
    total = total + quizScores[k];
    if (quizScores[k] < least) {
      least = quizScores[k];
    } // end-if
  } // end-for
  /* MISSING STATEMENT */
} // end method calculateFinalQuizScore

Which of the following can be used to replace /* MISSING STATEMENT */ so that calculateFinalQuizScore will work as intended?

Consider the following segment of code in a java-like programming language. Assume that there are no syntax errors.

int[] m = {2,3,4,5,6};
int n = 0;
int x = 0;
for (int val = 0; val < m.length; val++) {
 if (val % 2 == 1) {
      n = n + val;
      x = x + 1;
  } // end-if
} // end-for

What is the most likely use for the code segment above?
Answer: Calculating the total sum of the values held in array m.
